# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1945-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1945-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1945-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1945-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1945-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1945-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1945-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1945-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1945-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1945-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1945-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1945-world-series/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1945-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1945-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1945-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1945-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1945-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1945-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1945-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1878 Chicago White Stockings season** was the seventh season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third in the National League and the first at Lakefront Park.
[src:1945-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 30–30.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The **1945 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1945 season.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The 42nd edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion Detroit Tigers against the National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Tigers won the Series in seven games, giving them their second championship and first since 1935.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the decisive Game 7, Paul Richards drove in four runs to lead the Tigers to a 9–3 victory to clinch the Series.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The World Series again used the 3–4 wartime setup for home field sites, instead of the normal 2–3–2.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Although the major hostilities of World War II had ended, some of the rules were still in effect and many of the best MLB players were still in military service.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Warren Brown, author of a history of the Cubs in 1946, commented on this by titling one chapter "World's Worst Series".
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] He also cited a famous quote of his, referencing himself anonymously and in the third person.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] One player decidedly not fitting that description was the Tigers' slugger Hank Greenberg, who had been discharged from military service early.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] He hit the only two Tigers homers in the Series, and scored seven runs overall and also drove in seven.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The series matched the league MVPs, with Phil Cavarretta (a .355 hitter that year) of the National League and Hal Newhouser of the American League for the second straight season for Detroit.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Newhouser led the Tigers to two victories, including a complete game performance in Game 7.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Curse of the Billy Goat originated in this Series before the start of Game 4.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Having last won the Series in 1908, the Cubs owned the dubious record of both the longest league pennant drought and the longest World Series drought in history, not winning (or appearing in) another World Series until 2016.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Series was a rematch of the 1935 World Series.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In that year's Game 6, Stan Hack led off the top of the ninth inning with a triple, but was stranded.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] According to Warren Brown's account, Hack was seen surveying the field before the first Series game.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] To date, the Chicago Cubs have had no personnel from this team elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The visiting Cubs began with a bang, scoring four times in the first.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] With two outs and runners on first and third, a passed ball by future Hall of Famer Hal Newhouser scored the game's first run.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] After an intentional walk, a two-run Bill Nicholson double and Mickey Livingston's RBI single made it 4–0 Cubs.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the third, after a leadoff double, Phil Cavarretta's single and Andy Pafko's double scored a run each.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] One out later, Livingston's second RBI single of the game knocked Newhouser out of the game.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Cavarretta's two-out home run in the seventh off Jim Tobin made it 8–0.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Pafko then singled, stole second, moved to third on a passed ball, and scored the game's last run on Nicholson's single.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Hank Borowy pitched a complete-game shutout despite allowing 12 base runners as the Cubs took a 1–0 series lead.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] This was the first and only home run hit by the Cubs in the Series and Cavaretta's home run was the last postseason home run hit by a Cub until Bob Dernier did so in Game 1 of the 1984 National League Championship Series.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Cubs struck first when Phil Cavarretta doubled with one out in the fourth and scored on Bill Nicholson's single.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] After 13 innings without a run, Detroit finally got going in a big way in the fifth.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Hank Wyse got two outs, before allowing a single and walk.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Doc Cramer's RBI single tied the game before Hank Greenberg's three-run home run put the Tigers up 4–1.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Virgil Trucks allowed no other runs in a complete game as the Tigers tied the series at a game apiece.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Claude Passeau pitched a complete game one-hitter.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Tigers' only hit of the game came with two outs in the second inning off the bat of Rudy York.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Cubs scored two runs in the fourth off Stubby Overmire on RBI singles by Bill Nicholson and Roy Hughes after a leadoff double and one-out walk.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] They added another run in the seventh off Al Benton when Mickey Livingston hit a leadoff double, moved to third on a groundout and scored on Claude Passeau's sacrifice fly.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Series shifted to Wrigley Field and the so-called Curse of the Billy Goat began.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Dizzy Trout went the distance for Detroit with a five-hitter.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] A four-run fourth against Cub starter Ray Prim gave Trout all the runs he needed.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] After a one-out walk and single, Hank Greenberg's RBI single and Roy Cullenbine's RBI double knocked starter Ray Prim out of the game.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Paul Derringer intentionally walked Rudy York before Jimmy Outlaw's groundout and Paul Richards's single scored a run each.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Cubs scored their only run of the game in the sixth when Don Johnson hit a leadoff triple and scored on Peanuts Lowrey's groundout.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Back in form, Hal Newhouser went the distance for Detroit, striking out nine.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Tigers struck first in the top of the third on Doc Cramer's sacrifice fly with runners on first and third, but the Cubs tied the game in the bottom half when Hank Borowy doubled with two outs and scored on Stan Hack's single.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the sixth, Cramer hit a leadoff single and scored on Hank Greenberg's double.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] After a single, Rudy York's RBI single knocked starter Hank Borowy out of the game.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Hy Vandenberg in relief intentionally walked Paul Richards with one out to load the bases before a walk to Newhouser and Skeeter Webb's groundout scored a run each.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Next inning, Jimmy Outlaw's sacrifice fly with runners on first and third off Paul Derringer made it 6–1 Tigers.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, with runners on first and third with two outs, Bill Nicholson's fielder's choice and Mickey Livingston's ground-rule double scored a run each.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the ninth, after a hit-by-pitch and double, Roy Cullenbine's two-run double off Paul Erickson made it 8–3 Tigers.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the bottom half, Phil Cavarretta hit a leadoff double and scored on Nicholson's one out single before Newhouser retired the next two batters to end the game and put the Tigers one win away from the championship.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Cubs' World Series record at Wrigley Field now stood at 1–10.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In Game 6, the Tigers struck first on a bases-loaded walk to Paul Richards by Claude Passeau in the second.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the fifth with the bases loaded off Virgil Trucks, Stan Hack's two-run single put the Cubs up 2–1.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] After another walk loaded the bases, Phil Cavarretta's two-run single knocked Trucks out of the game.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Back-to-back leadoff doubles next inning by Mickey Livingston and Roy Hughes off Tommy Bridges made it 5–1 Cubs.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the top of the seventh with two on and two outs, RBI singles by Roy Cullenbine off Passeau and Rudy York off Hank Wyse cut the Cubs' lead to 5–3, but they got those runs back in the bottom half on a bases loaded walk to Livingston by Bridges followed by Roy Hughes's RBI single off Al Benton.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the top of the eighth, after a leadoff walk and double, an error on Joe Hoover's ground ball scored a run, then Eddie Mayo's RBI single scored another with Hoover going to third and Mayo being tagged out at second.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Ray Prim relieved Wyse and allowed a sacrifice fly to Doc Cramer before Hank Greenberg's home run tied the game.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the 12th, after a one-out single by Frank Secory off Dizzy Trout, pinch-runner Bill Schuster came all the way around on Stan Hack's walk-off double to left, forcing a Game 7.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Besides being the last World Series game the Cubs won until Game 2 in 2016, this would also be the second—and last—World Series game that the Cubs would win before their hometown fans at Wrigley Field, until Game 5 in 2016.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The only other Wrigley victory was Game 5 in 1935.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Cubs went with the overworked Borowy, who lasted just three batters, each of whom singled, the last of which scored a run.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Paul Derringer replaced him, intentionally walked Roy Cullenbine with one out to load the bases, then one out later, walked Jimmy Outlaw before Paul Richards cleared the bases with a three-run double.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Cubs got a run in the bottom of the first on Phil Cavarretta's RBI single with two on off Hal Newhouser, but in the second, Derringer allowed a two-out single, then three consecutive walks to force in another run.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Cubs got another run in the fourth when Cavaretta singled and scored on Andy Pafko's triple.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In the seventh, Cullenbine drew a leadoff walk off Paul Erickson and scored on Paul Richards's two-out double.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Next inning, Skeeter Webb drew a leadoff walk off Claude Passeau and scored on Eddie Mayo's double.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] After moving to third on a groundout, he scored on Hank Greenberg's sacrifice fly.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Cubs scored just one more run in the bottom of the inning on Bill Richardson's RBI double with two on as Newhouser pitched a complete game to give the Tigers the championship.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] This was the first Game 7 won by the Tigers in franchise history.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] The Tigers would not make another World Series appearance until winning it in 1968, while the Cubs would not make the postseason again until 1984 and not appear in another World Series until winning it in 2016.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] This was the last time the Tigers won the World Series until 1968, where they overcame a 3–1 series deficit to defeat the St.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] Louis Cardinals in seven games after being nine outs away from elimination in Game 5.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] After the series loss, the Cubs entered a decades long slump.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] In their next five attempts to win a league pennant (1969, 1984, 1989, 2003, 2015), the Cubs lost each time.
[src:1945-world-series/1945-world-series] They would not return to the Fall Classic until 2016, where they overcame a 3–1 series deficit against the Cleveland Indians and won in seven games after being taken to extra innings in Game 7, ending a 108-year championship drought.
